Defendant David Earl Crawford in court with Attorney Ann T. Bowe.  Defendant David Earl Crawford in custody.  Paul Leonard Tiffin appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Matter here for Sentencing.  Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.  Additional statements by:  Willie Mae E.  AS TO COUNT #1:  The Court imposed the following sentence:  The Defendant's TOTAL LENGTH OF SENTENCE shall be FOURTY-FIVE (45) years CONSECUTIVE TO 03CF5509.  Defendant's TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin Prison System shall be for THIRTY-FIVE (35) years.  Defendant shall serve TEN (10) years on EXTENDED SUPERVISION.

AS TO COUNT #2:  The Court imposed the following sentence:  The Defendant's TOTAL LENGTH OF SENTENCE shall be SEVEN (7) years CONSECUTIVE TO COUNT #1.  Defendant's TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin Prison System shall be for FIVE (5) years,  Defendant shall serve TWO (2) years on EXTENDED SUPERVISION.

The defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program;
The defendant is not eligible for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.  

The Court advised the defendant of the determinate sentence pursuant to statute and in accordance with Form CR-234.  Copy provided to defendant. 

Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess any gun or other firearms. 
Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.  

Court advised that the defendant will have to provide a DNA sample, to the Wisconsin State Crime Laboratory for DNA testing and pay a DNA surcharge.

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
 - No controlled substances or alcohol;
 - AODA assessment; treatment, if needed;
 - Random urine screens to ensure compliance;
 - No contact AT ALL with any of the victim's family;
 - Restitution is to be deteremined within SIXTY (60) days; 
 - Pay the DNA surcharge, costs and disbursements.  The Defendant shall pay restitution, fine and mandatory costs and surcharges from prison funds, including wages and all other moneys, in an amount or percentage the Department (DOC) determines to be reasonable and as a condition fo extended probation.  Balance would be then be paid while on Extended Supervision.  Failure to pay amounts in full would result in a civil judgment entered against defendant.

The Court ordered that restitution to be deteremined within SIXTY (60) DAYS.  Matter set for a restitution hearing on May 16, 2017 at 8:30am in Br. 30, Judge Conen's court.  The Court indicated that the Defendant can appear by video or telephone for that hearing.
